<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-503-471  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 503 471.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  Oct 8 1990 v7 n41 p9(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>OS/2 competition may turn budding relationship sour; IBM,Microsoft could divide over LAN Manager. (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Brown, Bob.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>IBM introduces the new 'lite', a memory intensive option to itsOS/2 Extended Edition.andP;  The 'lite' is 25 percent faster thanversion one and two of OS/2 and requires two megabytes of memoryenabling users to run large applications.andP;  The introduction of theOS/2 'lite' may prove effective for users wanting extra memory innetwork servers and workstations.andP;  The new product brings IBM indirect competition with its OS/2 operating systems partner,Microsoft Corp, developer of Windows 3.0.andP;  The two companies alsohave a LAN Manager marketing relationship that may be furthercomplicated if they are to compete with each other.andP;  Microsoft hasfor a while backed off its obligations to OS/2 and applied itsresources to a series of enhancements to make Windows 3.0 moreattractive as an operating systems.andP;  Both companies have consentedto IBM handling developments of the next two versions of OS/2.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (product introduction)Microsoft Corp. (equipment and supplies).andO;Ticker:    MSFT; IBM.andO;Product:   OS/2 PM Lite (Operating system) (product introduction)Microsoft Windows 3.0 (Graphical user interface) (productenhancement).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionOperating SystemsCompetitionMarket AnalysisGraphical User Interface.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>